james watt in Science            Expand


Watt, James  1736-1819.   British engineer and inventor who patented a much improved version of the steam engine (1769) and devised the unit of horsepower. The watt unit of power is named for him. 

watt




   (wŏt)    The SI derived unit used to measure power, equal to one joule per second. In electricity, a watt is equal to current (in amperes) multiplied by voltage (in volts). 

            The American Heritage® Science DictionaryCopyright © 2002. Published by Houghton Mifflin. All rights reserved.
